A declaration of peace between the leaders of Thailand and Cambodia, and a diplomatic accomplishment for President Donald Trump. For several days in July, these two kingdoms in Southeast Asia engaged in deadly fighting. The Thai and Cambodian militaries battled each other across stretches of their long, contested border, killing dozens and displacing some 200,000 people. Cambodia fired rockets while a tie of 16s carried out airstrikes. It was the worst violence between these two countries in generations. In late July, a lull in the fighting, after Trump declared, amid threats of imposing high tariffs, that Cambodia and Thailand agreed to immediately meet and quickly work out a ceasefire and ultimately peace. The next day, with the help of U.S. mediation, Cambodia's Prime Minister met his Thai counterpart in Malaysia to agree to a temporary ceasefire. Sunday's signing ceremony in Kuala Lumpur builds on those initial peace gains and marks a diplomatic victory for Trump and his often stated commitment to conflict resolution.
